\begin_layout Standard
The thermodynamical objects that we are interested in this paper are topological
 pressure and equilibrium states.
 For a continuous potential (i.e., function) 
\begin_inset Formula $\vp:T^{1}S\to\R$
\end_inset

, the 
\shape italic
topological pressure 
\shape default

\begin_inset Formula $P(\vp)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vp$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

 can be described by the 
\shape italic
variational principle
\shape default
: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\vp)=\sup\{h_{\mu}({\cal F})+\int\vp d\mu:\ \mu{\rm \ is\ }a\mbox{\ }{\cal F}-{\rm invariant\ }{\rm Borel\ }{\rm probability\ }{\rm measure}\}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu}({\cal F})$
\end_inset

 is the measure-theoretic entropy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

.
 An invariant Borel probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 achieving the supremum is called an 
\shape italic
equilibrium state
\shape default
.
 We notice that when 
\begin_inset Formula $\vp$
\end_inset

 is identically equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $P(0)$
\end_inset

 is equal to the topological entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{{\rm top}}({\cal F})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

, and equilibrium states for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vp\equiv0$
\end_inset

 are called 
\shape italic
measure of maximum entropy
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-uniform hyperbolicity of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

