Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a closed surface of genus greater than or equal to 2 without focal points,
 then the geodesic flow has a unique equilibrium state 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{q}$
\end_inset

 for the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $q\varphi^{u}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q<1$
\end_inset

.
 This equilibrium state 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{q}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{q}(\text{Reg})=1$
\end_inset

, is fully supported, Bernoulli, and is the weak* limit of weighted regular
 periodic orbits.
 Furthermore, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $q\mapsto P(q\vphi^{u})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q<1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P(q\vp^{u})=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\geq1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sing\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By the above lemma, Theorem A, and Theorem B, it remains to show 
\begin_inset Formula $q\mapsto P(q\vp^{u})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q<1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P(q\vp^{u})=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\geq1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sing\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 We first notice that when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sing\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(q\vp^{u})\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 It is because pick any invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm supp}(\mu)\subset\Sing$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{\mu}({\cal F})+\int_{T^{1}S}\vp^{u}d\mu=h_{\mu}({\cal F})+\int_{\Sing}\vp^{u}d\mu\geq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Moreover, the positive Lyapunov exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{+}$
\end_inset

 is the Birkhoff average of 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vp^{u}$
\end_inset

; thus together with Ruelle's inequality we have for any invariant measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\in{\cal M}({\cal F})$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{\nu}({\cal F})\leq\int_{T^{1}S}\chi^{+}(v)d\nu
\]

\end_inset

and for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\geq1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
h_{\nu}({\cal F})+\int\vp^{u}d\nu & =\underset{\leq0}{\underbrace{h_{\nu}({\cal F})-\int_{T^{1}S}\chi^{+}(v)d\nu}}\\
 & \geq h_{\nu}({\cal F})-q\int_{T^{1}S}\chi^{+}(v)d\nu\\
 & =h_{\nu}({\cal F})+q\int_{T^{1}S}\vp^{u}d\nu
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Therefore, we have for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\geq1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(q\vp^{u})=\sup\{h_{\nu}({\cal F})+q\int_{T^{1}S}\vp^{u}d\nu:\ {\cal \nu\in{\cal M}}({\cal F})\}\leq0;
\]

\end_inset

hence we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(q\vp^{u})=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\geq1$
\end_inset

.
